elements.2211.03231_355e910f5bfb8f10f1a363ff31628: Spectral methods provide consistent estimators for community detection in dense graphs
elements.2211.03231_633e9f167b92ec5ed3346030403e0: However, their performance deteriorates as the graphs become sparser
elements.2211.03231_fc31a0ae9a5ab9dde19d1f1e1ff60: In this work we consider a random graph model that can produce graphs at different levels of sparsity, and we show that graph neural networks can outperform spectral methods on sparse graphs
elements.2211.03231_56ea6d8c38fed741b27b7d9974b62: We illustrate the results with numerical examples in both synthetic and real graphs.
elements.2211.03231_ceee86711bbabde1ea176208994ce: Graph neural networks, community detection, spectral embedding
elements.2211.03231_70bbd20a7380d782bd7fbf3dfe530: Community detection is a fundamental problem in network science and highly relevant to graph signal processing
elements.2211.03231_4278bb45a9ea30d401f7a0a8034b7: Community in a graph refers to a group of nodes that are similar in terms of their connectivity structure and their attributes
elements.2211.03231_eb25d8e91bc74eef19201ccab6c92: Detecting communities reveals important graph structures which can be exploited in a variety of applications, including human neuroimaging
elements.2211.03231_450a776028d813c6ea9a738b9bbfc: Numerous approaches have been proposed for community detection, including graph neural networks (GNNs)
elements.2211.03231_8d247ab2f747bde1c26b943b94d4e: for a survey and references therein
elements.2211.03231_3a6dcc771ae898da7afd550aa2de1: In this paper, we focus on supervised community detection with GNNs
elements.2211.03231_f0db535176bd99f6eeea7e75038c2: We compare GNNs with spectral embeddings, a class of established statistical methods
elements.2211.03231_b5589f64a4da3a10348d4fffd1ae7: Spectral embeddings (SEs) have nice theoretical guarantees in random graph models, but can be computationally intensive in large graphs and brittle in sparse graphs
elements.2211.03231_916b73f85187fdea7ebddd6913cfb: On the other hand, GNNs are deep convolutional architectures for graph data
elements.2211.03231_8db2a0b25203ea5735f7d41b39249: enjoying desirable mathematical properties such as stability
elements.2211.03231_c3ec044fc16f2007c9db3e65fb638: , and showing remarkable empirical performance in a variety of problems on large-scale, sparse graphs
elements.2211.03231_864793b31b6eb5860df6c3cdaaccf: Motivated by these observations, we seek out to understand the theoretical underpinnings of the differences in behavior observed between GNNs and SEs in community detection on dense and sparse graphs
elements.2211.03231_f0694e65b200d71951c2ee8736e4c: To this end, we propose a random graph model that can generate graphs with variable sparsity (Def.
elements.2211.03231_82b675c241aab6cc0e72893326afe: We then use it to prove that SEs degrade with graph sparsity (Thm.
elements.2211.03231_2e48893ee7adff6ca0a1b18703ba8: ), and to explain why GNNs perform consistently well in sparse graphs (Thm.
elements.2211.03231_75c50aeb2bb02a4541f7550e84937: These findings are further demonstrated empirically through numerical experiments on both synthetic and real-world graphs (Sec.
